{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9ba8451b-f96e-4736-a07c-da43ef6e0310","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on that topic, but I can answer from general .NET knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n\n2. **Reproduce the crash.** macOS will write a core file to the configured path (e.g., `/tmp/core.<pid>`).\n\n3. **Check Apple's Crash Reporter** — macOS also writes `.crash` logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Inside lldb you can use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `register read`, etc.\n\n5. **For managed stack traces**, load the SOS/dotnet diagnostics plugin in lldb:\n   ```bash\n   plugin load /path/to/libsosplugin.dylib\n   ```\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT apps are fully ahead-of-time compiled, so standard `lldb` with debug symbols (`.dSYM`) is usually sufficient — you don't strictly need SOS for stack traces if you published with symbols.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3900da73-c504-4a7a-8998-e5686aaf4c31","outputTokens":341},"id":"dfdd12b1-6bf1-4bd4-a63e-db7a4565e399","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:02:12.695Z","parentId":"83755181-3067-491b-94ef-fb0585c81fb7"}
{"type":"assistant.turn_end","data":{"turnId":"2"},"id":"8abe48c7-fd92-403f-970f-fc42cc82a5e1","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:02:12.703Z","parentId":"dfdd12b1-6bf1-4bd4-a63e-db7a4565e399"}
